{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012VRf36wfewQsSHFwoPfxnD","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\n    10→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearLimitations\n    11→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HTemporalTheorems\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E88ExceedsE1HCapacity\n    13→\n    14→/-!\n    15→# The Full Expressivity Hierarchy: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H ⊊ E88\n    16→\n    17→This file proves the main expressivity hierarchy theorem, establishing\n    18→two strict containments in the expressivity ordering:\n    19→\n    20→```\n    21→Linear SSM  ⊊  E1H  ⊊  E88\n    22→```\n    23→\n    24→## Architecture Summary\n    25→\n    26→| Architecture | State         | Update                             | Scalars/head |\n    27→|--------------|---------------|------------------------------------|--------------|\n    28→| Linear SSM   | D-vector h    | h := A·h + B·x  (linear)          | D            |\n    29→| E1H          | D-vector h    | h := tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)      | D            |\n    30→| E88          | D×D matrix S  | S := tanh(α·S + δ·outer(v,k))     | D²           |\n    31→\n    32→## Separation Witnesses\n    33→\n    34→### Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n    35→\n    36→**Negative (Linear SSM cannot)**:\n    37→- `linear_cannot_threshold`: Threshold functions are not linearly computable\n    38→  (proven via continuity/linearity argument in `LinearLimitations`)\n    39→- `linear_cannot_xor`: XOR is not linearly computable\n    40→  (proven via affine impossibility in `LinearLimitations`)\n    41→\n    42→**Positive (E1H can)**:\n    43→- `e1h_threshold_capability`: E1H has saturation-regime parameters (α ∈ (1,2))\n    44→  enabling threshold-like dynamics; the tanh gate creates stable attractors\n    45→- E1H is fundamentally nonlinear (tanh gate), while Linear SSMs are linear\n    46→\n    47→### E1H ⊊ E88\n    48→\n    49→**Capacity separation** (from `E88ExceedsE1HCapacity` and `E1HDefinition`):\n    50→- E88 state: D×D matrix → D² scalars per head\n    51→- E1H state: D-vector → D scalars per head\n    52→- For D ≥ 2: D² > D, so E88 stores strictly more information per head\n    53→\n    54→**Content-addressable retrieval** (E88 unique capability):\n    55→- E88: S·q reads state by query content (matrix × vector)\n    56→- E1H: no matrix to multiply; cannot do content-addressable retrieval\n    57→- `e88_addressable_e1h_not` demonstrates two queries returning different values from same E88 state\n    58→\n    59→## Connection to CMA-ES Empirical Results\n    60→\n    61→At 32K context length, empirical perplexity ordering:\n    62→- E88: ~1.100 (best)\n    63→- E1H: ~1.190 (middle)\n    64→- Mamba2 (Linear SSM): 1.188 (worst)\n    65→\n    66→The strict hierarchy proven here explains why E88 < E1H < Mamba2 in perplexity\n    67→(lower is better): each strictly more expressive architecture better models language.\n    68→\n    69→## Main Theorem\n    70→\n    71→* `hierarchy` - The full three-way strict expressivity hierarchy\n    72→\n    73→## Intermediate Theorems\n    74→\n    75→* `linearSSM_strictly_below_e1h` - Linear SSM < E1H separation\n    76→* `e1h_strictly_below_e88` - E1H < E88 separation\n    77→\n    78→-/\n    79→\n    80→namespace ExpressivityHierarchy\n    81→\n    82→open Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    83→\n    84→/-! ## Part 1: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n    85→\n    86→The key separating witness: threshold function.\n    87→- Linear SSMs cannot compute threshold (output is always linear in inputs)\n    88→- E1H CAN implement threshold-like dynamics (tanh saturation regime)\n    89→-/\n    90→\n    91→/-- **Linear SSM cannot compute threshold**.\n    92→\n    93→For any threshold τ and sequence length T ≥ 1, the threshold function\n    94→(output 1 if sum of inputs > τ, else 0) is NOT linearly computable.\n    95→\n    96→Proof: Assume linear RNN computes threshold. Then the output is a linear\n    97→function g(x) = c·x of the scalar input. But threshold has a jump at τ,\n    98→while linear functions are continuous and do not jump. Specifically:\n    99→- g(τ-1) = 0 and g(τ+1) = 1 requires g(1) = 1/(τ+1) ... -/\n   100→theorem linearSSM_cannot_threshold (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ) (hT : T ≥ 1) :\n   101→    ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction τ T) :=\n   102→  Expressivity.linear_cannot_threshold τ T hT\n   103→\n   104→/-- **Linear SSM cannot compute XOR**.\n   105→\n   106→XOR on binary {0,1}² inputs is not linearly computable.\n   107→\n   108→Proof: Any linear function satisfies f(0,0) + f(1,1) = f(0,1) + f(1,0),\n   109→but XOR gives 0 + 0 ≠ 1 + 1. Contradiction. -/\n   110→theorem linearSSM_cannot_xor :\n   111→    ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable\n   112→      (fun (inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) (_ : Fin 1) =>\n   113→        Expressivity.xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0)) :=\n   114→  Expressivity.linear_cannot_xor\n   115→\n   116→/-- **E1H has threshold capability via tanh saturation**.\n   117→\n   118→E1H can implement threshold-like dynamics: there exists a 1D E1H head\n   119→with recurrence weight α ∈ (1,2) (the saturation regime). In this regime,\n   120→the fixed point dynamics behave like a threshold:\n   121→- Small inputs → state near 0\n   122→- Large cumulative input → state near ±1 (saturated)\n   123→\n   124→This is the threshold capability that linear SSMs fundamentally lack. -/\n   125→theorem e1h_threshold_capability :\n   126→    ∃ (head : E1H.E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n   127→      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n   128→      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   129→      1 < α ∧ α < 2 :=\n   130→  E1HTemporalTheorems.e1h_can_threshold\n   131→\n   132→/-- **E1H has nonlinear compositional depth T**.\n   133→\n   134→E1H applies T sequential nonlinear tanh compositions, giving compositional\n   135→depth T. Linear SSMs collapse to a single linear combination (effective depth 1).\n   136→This depth difference is the mechanism behind E1H's strictly greater expressivity. -/\n   137→theorem e1h_has_depth_T (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n   138→    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length T\n   139→    let e1h_depth := T\n   140→    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n   141→    let linear_depth := 1\n   142→    -- E1H strictly exceeds linear depth\n   143→    e1h_depth > linear_depth ∧\n   144→    -- E1H depth matches E88 depth (same recurrence structure)\n   145→    e1h_depth = T :=\n   146→  E1HTemporalTheorems.e1h_has_depth_T T h_T\n   147→\n   148→/-- **STRICT SEPARATION: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H**.\n   149→\n   150→Three evidence points:\n   151→1. Linear SSMs cannot compute threshold (separating function witness)\n   152→2. E1H CAN implement threshold dynamics (saturation regime)\n   153→3. Linear SSMs cannot compute XOR (second separating witness) -/\n   154→theorem linearSSM_strictly_below_e1h :\n   155→    -- (1) Linear SSM cannot compute threshold functions\n   156→    (∀ (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ), T ≥ 1 →\n   157→      ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction τ T)) ∧\n   158→    -- (2) E1H can implement threshold-like behavior (saturation regime)\n   159→    (∃ (head : E1H.E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n   160→      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧ let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n   161→    -- (3) Linear SSM cannot compute XOR\n   162→    (¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable\n   163→      (fun (inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) (_ : Fin 1) =>\n   164→        Expressivity.xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0))) := by\n   165→  refine ⟨fun τ T hT => linearSSM_cannot_threshold τ T hT,\n   166→          e1h_threshold_capability,\n   167→          linearSSM_cannot_xor⟩\n   168→\n   169→/-! ## Part 2: E1H ⊊ E88\n   170→\n   171→The key separation: matrix state capacity.\n   172→- E1H: D scalars per head (D-vector state)\n   173→- E88: D² scalars per head (D×D matrix state)\n   174→- For D ≥ 2: D² > D strictly\n   175→- E88 supports S·q content-addressable retrieval that E1H fundamentally cannot\n   176→-/\n   177→\n   178→/-- **E88 state capacity D² strictly exceeds E1H capacity D**.\n   179→\n   180→For head dimension D ≥ 2:\n   181→- E1H state: Fin D → ℝ with |Fin D| = D scalar entries\n   182→- E88 state: Fin D × Fin D → ℝ with |Fin D × Fin D| = D² scalar entries\n   183→- D² > D for all D ≥ 2\n   184→\n   185→This is the quantitative foundation of E88's superiority over E1H. -/\n   186→theorem e88_capacity_strictly_exceeds_e1h (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   187→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d :=\n   188→  E1H.e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state d hd\n   189→\n   190→/-- **E88 supports content-addressable retrieval; E1H cannot**.\n   191→\n   192→E88's D×D matrix state S enables content-based retrieval via S·q:\n   193→- Store S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (association: query e₀ → value e₀)\n   194→- Query e₀: retrieves e₀ (nonzero)\n   195→- Query e₁ ⊥ e₀: retrieves 0 (orthogonal → nothing)\n   196→- Different queries → different values: THIS is content-addressable\n   197→\n   198→E1H's D-vector state h cannot support this:\n   199→- Any \"read\" from h is a fixed linear projection\n   200→- There is no matrix to multiply against a query vector\n   201→- So E1H cannot implement key-based addressing\n   202→\n   203→This structural difference explains why E88 can implement associative\n   204→memories (key-value stores) that E1H cannot. -/\n   205→theorem e88_content_addressable_e1h_not (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   206→    ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n   207→      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧\n   208→      CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₂ :=\n   209→  CapacitySeparation.e88_addressable_e1h_not d hd\n   210→\n   211→/-- **Total state separation**: E88 total scalars (H × D²) > E1H total scalars (H × D).\n   212→\n   213→Across all H heads, E88 stores H·D² scalars while E1H stores H·D scalars.\n   214→For H ≥ 1, D ≥ 2: H·D² > H·D. -/\n   215→theorem e88_total_capacity_exceeds_e1h (numHeads d : ℕ) (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n   216→    E1H.e1hTotalState numHeads d < E1H.e88TotalState numHeads d :=\n   217→  E1H.e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h numHeads d hH hd\n   218→\n   219→/-- **STRICT SEPARATION: E1H ⊊ E88**.\n   220→\n   221→Two evidence points:\n   222→1. E88 state capacity D² strictly exceeds E1H capacity D (for D ≥ 2)\n   223→2. E88 supports content-addressable retrieval impossible for E1H -/\n   224→theorem e1h_strictly_below_e88 :\n   225→    -- (1) E88 state capacity strictly exceeds E1H for any D ≥ 2\n   226→    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n   227→      E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d) ∧\n   228→    -- (2) E88 supports content-addressable retrieval that E1H cannot do\n   229→    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n   230→      ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n   231→        q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧\n   232→        CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₂) := by\n   233→  exact ⟨fun d hd => e88_capacity_strictly_exceeds_e1h d hd,\n   234→         fun d hd => e88_content_addressable_e1h_not d hd⟩\n   235→\n   236→/-! ## The Full Hierarchy Theorem -/\n   237→\n   238→/-- **MAIN THEOREM: The Full Expressivity Hierarchy**\n   239→\n   240→```\n   241→  Linear SSM  ⊊  E1H  ⊊  E88\n   242→```\n   243→\n   244→This theorem establishes strict containments at both levels:\n   245→\n   246→### Level 1: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n   247→\n   248→- **Linear SSM limitation**: Cannot compute threshold or XOR functions\n   249→  (output is always a linear/affine function of the input sequence)\n   250→- **E1H capability**: Has tanh saturation regime (α ∈ (1,2)) enabling\n   251→  threshold dynamics; applies T nonlinear compositions (depth T vs linear's depth 1)\n   252→\n   253→### Level 2: E1H ⊊ E88\n   254→\n   255→- **E1H limitation**: D-vector state per head → only D scalar parameters\n   256→  Cannot implement S·q content-addressable retrieval (no matrix state)\n   257→- **E88 capability**: D×D matrix state per head → D² scalar parameters\n   258→  Supports content-addressable retrieval; can distinguish queries via S·q\n   259→\n   260→### Empirical Correlation\n   261→\n   262→These theoretical separations predict the observed CMA-ES perplexity ordering\n   263→at 32K context: E88 (1.100) < E1H (~1.190) < Mamba2 (1.188) (lower = better):\n   264→- Mamba2 is a linear SSM; limited to linear expressivity\n   265→- E1H adds nonlinear tanh depth; improves over Mamba2\n   266→- E88 adds matrix state capacity (D² > D); further improves over E1H -/\n   267→theorem hierarchy :\n   268→    -- PART 1: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n   269→    -- (a) Linear SSMs cannot compute threshold\n   270→    (∀ (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ), T ≥ 1 →\n   271→      ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction τ T)) ∧\n   272→    -- (b) E1H threshold capability: saturation regime exists\n   273→    (∃ (head : E1H.E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n   274→      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧ let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n   275→    -- (c) Linear SSMs cannot compute XOR\n   276→    (¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable\n   277→      (fun (inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) (_ : Fin 1) =>\n   278→        Expressivity.xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0))) ∧\n   279→    -- PART 2: E1H ⊊ E88\n   280→    -- (d) E88 state capacity strictly exceeds E1H (for D ≥ 2)\n   281→    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n   282→      E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d) ∧\n   283→    -- (e) E88 supports content-addressable retrieval; E1H (vector state) cannot\n   284→    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n   285→      ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n   286→        q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧\n   287→        CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₂) := by\n   288→  refine ⟨fun τ T hT => linearSSM_cannot_threshold τ T hT,\n   289→          e1h_threshold_capability,\n   290→          linearSSM_cannot_xor,\n   291→          fun d hd => e88_capacity_strictly_exceeds_e1h d hd,\n   292→          fun d hd => e88_content_addressable_e1h_not d hd⟩\n   293→\n   294→/-! ## Concrete Numerical Example (D = 2) -/\n   295→\n   296→/-- For D = 2, the concrete capacity separation:\n   297→    E88 has 4 scalar entries per head, E1H has 2. -/\n   298→theorem hierarchy_example_d2 :\n   299→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 = 2 ∧\n   300→    E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 = 4 ∧\n   301→    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 := by\n   302→  simp [E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead, E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead]\n   303→\n   304→/-- For D = 2 threshold at τ = 0, T = 1: concrete linear SSM limitation -/\n   305→theorem hierarchy_threshold_d1 :\n   306→    ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction 0 1) :=\n   307→  linearSSM_cannot_threshold 0 1 (by norm_num)\n   308→\n   309→end ExpressivityHierarchy\n   310→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6b651675-b913-4caf-818d-91bf4c46cc1f","uuid":"ac779a56-440b-40dc-a7e3-7edf19ff2220","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/ExpressivityHierarchy.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.LinearLimitations\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HTemporalTheorems\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E88ExceedsE1HCapacity\n\n/-!\n# The Full Expressivity Hierarchy: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H ⊊ E88\n\nThis file proves the main expressivity hierarchy theorem, establishing\ntwo strict containments in the expressivity ordering:\n\n```\nLinear SSM  ⊊  E1H  ⊊  E88\n```\n\n## Architecture Summary\n\n| Architecture | State         | Update                             | Scalars/head |\n|--------------|---------------|------------------------------------|--------------|\n| Linear SSM   | D-vector h    | h := A·h + B·x  (linear)          | D            |\n| E1H          | D-vector h    | h := tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)      | D            |\n| E88          | D×D matrix S  | S := tanh(α·S + δ·outer(v,k))     | D²           |\n\n## Separation Witnesses\n\n### Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n\n**Negative (Linear SSM cannot)**:\n- `linear_cannot_threshold`: Threshold functions are not linearly computable\n  (proven via continuity/linearity argument in `LinearLimitations`)\n- `linear_cannot_xor`: XOR is not linearly computable\n  (proven via affine impossibility in `LinearLimitations`)\n\n**Positive (E1H can)**:\n- `e1h_threshold_capability`: E1H has saturation-regime parameters (α ∈ (1,2))\n  enabling threshold-like dynamics; the tanh gate creates stable attractors\n- E1H is fundamentally nonlinear (tanh gate), while Linear SSMs are linear\n\n### E1H ⊊ E88\n\n**Capacity separation** (from `E88ExceedsE1HCapacity` and `E1HDefinition`):\n- E88 state: D×D matrix → D² scalars per head\n- E1H state: D-vector → D scalars per head\n- For D ≥ 2: D² > D, so E88 stores strictly more information per head\n\n**Content-addressable retrieval** (E88 unique capability):\n- E88: S·q reads state by query content (matrix × vector)\n- E1H: no matrix to multiply; cannot do content-addressable retrieval\n- `e88_addressable_e1h_not` demonstrates two queries returning different values from same E88 state\n\n## Connection to CMA-ES Empirical Results\n\nAt 32K context length, empirical perplexity ordering:\n- E88: ~1.100 (best)\n- E1H: ~1.190 (middle)\n- Mamba2 (Linear SSM): 1.188 (worst)\n\nThe strict hierarchy proven here explains why E88 < E1H < Mamba2 in perplexity\n(lower is better): each strictly more expressive architecture better models language.\n\n## Main Theorem\n\n* `hierarchy` - The full three-way strict expressivity hierarchy\n\n## Intermediate Theorems\n\n* `linearSSM_strictly_below_e1h` - Linear SSM < E1H separation\n* `e1h_strictly_below_e88` - E1H < E88 separation\n\n-/\n\nnamespace ExpressivityHierarchy\n\nopen Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\n/-! ## Part 1: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n\nThe key separating witness: threshold function.\n- Linear SSMs cannot compute threshold (output is always linear in inputs)\n- E1H CAN implement threshold-like dynamics (tanh saturation regime)\n-/\n\n/-- **Linear SSM cannot compute threshold**.\n\nFor any threshold τ and sequence length T ≥ 1, the threshold function\n(output 1 if sum of inputs > τ, else 0) is NOT linearly computable.\n\nProof: Assume linear RNN computes threshold. Then the output is a linear\nfunction g(x) = c·x of the scalar input. But threshold has a jump at τ,\nwhile linear functions are continuous and do not jump. Specifically:\n- g(τ-1) = 0 and g(τ+1) = 1 requires g(1) = 1/(τ+1) ... -/\ntheorem linearSSM_cannot_threshold (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ) (hT : T ≥ 1) :\n    ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction τ T) :=\n  Expressivity.linear_cannot_threshold τ T hT\n\n/-- **Linear SSM cannot compute XOR**.\n\nXOR on binary {0,1}² inputs is not linearly computable.\n\nProof: Any linear function satisfies f(0,0) + f(1,1) = f(0,1) + f(1,0),\nbut XOR gives 0 + 0 ≠ 1 + 1. Contradiction. -/\ntheorem linearSSM_cannot_xor :\n    ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable\n      (fun (inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) (_ : Fin 1) =>\n        Expressivity.xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0)) :=\n  Expressivity.linear_cannot_xor\n\n/-- **E1H has threshold capability via tanh saturation**.\n\nE1H can implement threshold-like dynamics: there exists a 1D E1H head\nwith recurrence weight α ∈ (1,2) (the saturation regime). In this regime,\nthe fixed point dynamics behave like a threshold:\n- Small inputs → state near 0\n- Large cumulative input → state near ±1 (saturated)\n\nThis is the threshold capability that linear SSMs fundamentally lack. -/\ntheorem e1h_threshold_capability :\n    ∃ (head : E1H.E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n      1 < α ∧ α < 2 :=\n  E1HTemporalTheorems.e1h_can_threshold\n\n/-- **E1H has nonlinear compositional depth T**.\n\nE1H applies T sequential nonlinear tanh compositions, giving compositional\ndepth T. Linear SSMs collapse to a single linear combination (effective depth 1).\nThis depth difference is the mechanism behind E1H's strictly greater expressivity. -/\ntheorem e1h_has_depth_T (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length T\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    let linear_depth := 1\n    -- E1H strictly exceeds linear depth\n    e1h_depth > linear_depth ∧\n    -- E1H depth matches E88 depth (same recurrence structure)\n    e1h_depth = T :=\n  E1HTemporalTheorems.e1h_has_depth_T T h_T\n\n/-- **STRICT SEPARATION: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H**.\n\nThree evidence points:\n1. Linear SSMs cannot compute threshold (separating function witness)\n2. E1H CAN implement threshold dynamics (saturation regime)\n3. Linear SSMs cannot compute XOR (second separating witness) -/\ntheorem linearSSM_strictly_below_e1h :\n    -- (1) Linear SSM cannot compute threshold functions\n    (∀ (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ), T ≥ 1 →\n      ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction τ T)) ∧\n    -- (2) E1H can implement threshold-like behavior (saturation regime)\n    (∃ (head : E1H.E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧ let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n    -- (3) Linear SSM cannot compute XOR\n    (¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable\n      (fun (inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) (_ : Fin 1) =>\n        Expressivity.xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0))) := by\n  refine ⟨fun τ T hT => linearSSM_cannot_threshold τ T hT,\n          e1h_threshold_capability,\n          linearSSM_cannot_xor⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 2: E1H ⊊ E88\n\nThe key separation: matrix state capacity.\n- E1H: D scalars per head (D-vector state)\n- E88: D² scalars per head (D×D matrix state)\n- For D ≥ 2: D² > D strictly\n- E88 supports S·q content-addressable retrieval that E1H fundamentally cannot\n-/\n\n/-- **E88 state capacity D² strictly exceeds E1H capacity D**.\n\nFor head dimension D ≥ 2:\n- E1H state: Fin D → ℝ with |Fin D| = D scalar entries\n- E88 state: Fin D × Fin D → ℝ with |Fin D × Fin D| = D² scalar entries\n- D² > D for all D ≥ 2\n\nThis is the quantitative foundation of E88's superiority over E1H. -/\ntheorem e88_capacity_strictly_exceeds_e1h (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d :=\n  E1H.e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state d hd\n\n/-- **E88 supports content-addressable retrieval; E1H cannot**.\n\nE88's D×D matrix state S enables content-based retrieval via S·q:\n- Store S = e₀ ⊗ e₀ᵀ (association: query e₀ → value e₀)\n- Query e₀: retrieves e₀ (nonzero)\n- Query e₁ ⊥ e₀: retrieves 0 (orthogonal → nothing)\n- Different queries → different values: THIS is content-addressable\n\nE1H's D-vector state h cannot support this:\n- Any \"read\" from h is a fixed linear projection\n- There is no matrix to multiply against a query vector\n- So E1H cannot implement key-based addressing\n\nThis structural difference explains why E88 can implement associative\nmemories (key-value stores) that E1H cannot. -/\ntheorem e88_content_addressable_e1h_not (d : ℕ) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n      q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧\n      CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₂ :=\n  CapacitySeparation.e88_addressable_e1h_not d hd\n\n/-- **Total state separation**: E88 total scalars (H × D²) > E1H total scalars (H × D).\n\nAcross all H heads, E88 stores H·D² scalars while E1H stores H·D scalars.\nFor H ≥ 1, D ≥ 2: H·D² > H·D. -/\ntheorem e88_total_capacity_exceeds_e1h (numHeads d : ℕ) (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hd : d ≥ 2) :\n    E1H.e1hTotalState numHeads d < E1H.e88TotalState numHeads d :=\n  E1H.e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h numHeads d hH hd\n\n/-- **STRICT SEPARATION: E1H ⊊ E88**.\n\nTwo evidence points:\n1. E88 state capacity D² strictly exceeds E1H capacity D (for D ≥ 2)\n2. E88 supports content-addressable retrieval impossible for E1H -/\ntheorem e1h_strictly_below_e88 :\n    -- (1) E88 state capacity strictly exceeds E1H for any D ≥ 2\n    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n      E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d) ∧\n    -- (2) E88 supports content-addressable retrieval that E1H cannot do\n    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n      ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n        q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧\n        CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₂) := by\n  exact ⟨fun d hd => e88_capacity_strictly_exceeds_e1h d hd,\n         fun d hd => e88_content_addressable_e1h_not d hd⟩\n\n/-! ## The Full Hierarchy Theorem -/\n\n/-- **MAIN THEOREM: The Full Expressivity Hierarchy**\n\n```\n  Linear SSM  ⊊  E1H  ⊊  E88\n```\n\nThis theorem establishes strict containments at both levels:\n\n### Level 1: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n\n- **Linear SSM limitation**: Cannot compute threshold or XOR functions\n  (output is always a linear/affine function of the input sequence)\n- **E1H capability**: Has tanh saturation regime (α ∈ (1,2)) enabling\n  threshold dynamics; applies T nonlinear compositions (depth T vs linear's depth 1)\n\n### Level 2: E1H ⊊ E88\n\n- **E1H limitation**: D-vector state per head → only D scalar parameters\n  Cannot implement S·q content-addressable retrieval (no matrix state)\n- **E88 capability**: D×D matrix state per head → D² scalar parameters\n  Supports content-addressable retrieval; can distinguish queries via S·q\n\n### Empirical Correlation\n\nThese theoretical separations predict the observed CMA-ES perplexity ordering\nat 32K context: E88 (1.100) < E1H (~1.190) < Mamba2 (1.188) (lower = better):\n- Mamba2 is a linear SSM; limited to linear expressivity\n- E1H adds nonlinear tanh depth; improves over Mamba2\n- E88 adds matrix state capacity (D² > D); further improves over E1H -/\ntheorem hierarchy :\n    -- PART 1: Linear SSM ⊊ E1H\n    -- (a) Linear SSMs cannot compute threshold\n    (∀ (τ : ℝ) (T : ℕ), T ≥ 1 →\n      ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction τ T)) ∧\n    -- (b) E1H threshold capability: saturation regime exists\n    (∃ (head : E1H.E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧ let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n    -- (c) Linear SSMs cannot compute XOR\n    (¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable\n      (fun (inputs : Fin 2 → (Fin 1 → ℝ)) (_ : Fin 1) =>\n        Expressivity.xorReal (inputs 0 0) (inputs 1 0))) ∧\n    -- PART 2: E1H ⊊ E88\n    -- (d) E88 state capacity strictly exceeds E1H (for D ≥ 2)\n    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n      E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead d < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead d) ∧\n    -- (e) E88 supports content-addressable retrieval; E1H (vector state) cannot\n    (∀ d : ℕ, d ≥ 2 →\n      ∃ (S : Matrix (Fin d) (Fin d) ℝ) (q₁ q₂ : Fin d → ℝ),\n        q₁ ≠ q₂ ∧\n        CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₁ ≠ CapacitySeparation.e88ContentRead S q₂) := by\n  refine ⟨fun τ T hT => linearSSM_cannot_threshold τ T hT,\n          e1h_threshold_capability,\n          linearSSM_cannot_xor,\n          fun d hd => e88_capacity_strictly_exceeds_e1h d hd,\n          fun d hd => e88_content_addressable_e1h_not d hd⟩\n\n/-! ## Concrete Numerical Example (D = 2) -/\n\n/-- For D = 2, the concrete capacity separation:\n    E88 has 4 scalar entries per head, E1H has 2. -/\ntheorem hierarchy_example_d2 :\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 = 2 ∧\n    E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 = 4 ∧\n    E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead 2 < E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead 2 := by\n  simp [E1H.e1hStateScalarsPerHead, E1H.e88StateScalarsPerHead]\n\n/-- For D = 2 threshold at τ = 0, T = 1: concrete linear SSM limitation -/\ntheorem hierarchy_threshold_d1 :\n    ¬ Expressivity.LinearlyComputable (Expressivity.thresholdFunction 0 1) :=\n  linearSSM_cannot_threshold 0 1 (by norm_num)\n\nend ExpressivityHierarchy\n","numLines":310,"startLine":1,"totalLines":310}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01XNawAtaN3qo7TYdiwRqgVM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01TSPuYztbjnBErUic4tBqvk","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HDefinition.lean"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4630,"cache_read_input_tokens":29093,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4630},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6b651675-b913-4caf-818d-91bf4c46cc1f","uuid":"6cf38665-8909-412f-a915-5cc7ee6acbf8"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TSPuYztbjnBErUic4tBqvk","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\n    10→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\n    11→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\n    13→\n    14→/-!\n    15→# E1H: Multi-Head Elman (Vector State)\n    16→\n    17→This file provides the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for E1H architecture formalization.\n    18→\n    19→## E1H Architecture\n    20→\n    21→E1H is a multi-head Elman recurrent network with:\n    22→1. **Multi-head vector states**: H heads, each with a vector state of dimension D\n    23→2. **Elman temporal dynamics**: h_t = tanh(W_x·x_t + W_h·h_{t-1} + b)\n    24→3. **Independent head evolution**: Each head runs autonomous temporal dynamics\n    25→4. **No decay factor**: Unlike E88, there is no separate α decay scalar\n    26→5. **No outer product**: Unlike E88, the state update is not an outer product operation\n    27→\n    28→## Core Update Rule\n    29→\n    30→For each head h:\n    31→```\n    32→h_t^h = tanh(W_x^h · x_t + W_h^h · h_{t-1}^h + b^h)\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→Where:\n    36→- h ∈ ℝ^D: Vector hidden state for head h (NOT a D×D matrix like E88)\n    37→- W_x ∈ ℝ^{D×inputDim}: Input projection matrix\n    38→- W_h ∈ ℝ^{D×D}: Recurrence (state-to-state) weight matrix\n    39→- b ∈ ℝ^D: Bias vector\n    40→- tanh: Applied element-wise to the resulting vector\n    41→\n    42→## Key Differences from E88\n    43→\n    44→| Property        | E88                      | E1H                           |\n    45→|-----------------|--------------------------|-------------------------------|\n    46→| State shape     | D×D matrix per head      | D-vector per head             |\n    47→| State dimension | D² scalars per head      | D scalars per head            |\n    48→| Update          | tanh(α·S + δ·outer(v,k)) | tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)      |\n    49→| Decay factor    | α ∈ (0, 2)               | None (folded into W_h)        |\n    50→| Input coupling  | Outer product (rank-1)   | Full matrix-vector product    |\n    51→| Parameters      | K_h, V_h + scalars       | W_x_h, W_h_h, b_h             |\n    52→\n    53→## Key Properties\n    54→\n    55→1. **Shared Temporal Depth**: Both E1H and E88 have compositional depth T per layer\n    56→2. **Vector vs Matrix Capacity**: E88 state has D² entries vs E1H's D entries per head\n    57→3. **Head Independence**: Each head evolves independently (like E88)\n    58→4. **Tanh Boundedness**: h_t ∈ [-1, 1]^D at all times\n    59→\n    60→## Main Results\n    61→\n    62→* `e1hHeadUpdate` - Core per-head update function\n    63→* `e1hHeadStateAfterT` - Single-head state after T steps\n    64→* `e1hMultiHeadState` - Multi-head state evolution\n    65→* `e1h_heads_independent` - Heads evolve independently\n    66→* `e1h_state_bounded` - States are bounded in [-1, 1]^D\n    67→* `e1h_temporal_depth` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n    68→* `e1h_vector_state_dimension` - E1H state has D scalars per head (vs D² for E88)\n    69→\n    70→-/\n    71→\n    72→namespace E1H\n    73→\n    74→open Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n    75→\n    76→/-! ## Part 1: E1H Core Architecture -/\n    77→\n    78→/-- E1H single-head configuration.\n    79→    Each head maintains a D-dimensional vector state (not a matrix like E88). -/\n    80→structure E1HHead (inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n    81→  /-- Input projection matrix W_x: headDim × inputDim -/\n    82→  inputProj : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin inputDim) ℝ\n    83→  /-- Recurrence weight matrix W_h: headDim × headDim -/\n    84→  recurrenceWeight : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin headDim) ℝ\n    85→  /-- Bias vector b: headDim -/\n    86→  bias : Fin headDim → ℝ\n    87→\n    88→/-- E1H multi-head model.\n    89→    H independent Elman RNN heads with shared input via a single in-projection. -/\n    90→structure E1HModel (numHeads inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n    91→  /-- Configuration for each head -/\n    92→  heads : Fin numHeads → E1HHead inputDim headDim\n    93→  /-- Output projection from all head states concatenated -/\n    94→  outputProj : Matrix (Fin inputDim) (Fin (numHeads * headDim)) ℝ\n    95→\n    96→/-- Vector hidden state for a single E1H head.\n    97→    This is a D-dimensional vector, NOT a D×D matrix like E88's HeadState. -/\n    98→abbrev E1HHeadState (headDim : ℕ) := Fin headDim → ℝ\n    99→\n   100→/-- E1H state for all heads: a vector state per head. -/\n   101→abbrev E1HState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) := Fin numHeads → E1HHeadState headDim\n   102→\n   103→/-! ## Part 2: E1H State Update Dynamics -/\n   104→\n   105→/-- Element-wise tanh applied to a vector -/\n   106→noncomputable def vecTanh {n : ℕ} (v : Fin n → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n   107→  fun i => tanh (v i)\n   108→\n   109→/-- Single-head E1H state update: h' = tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)\n   110→    This is the standard Elman recurrence with full matrix projections.\n   111→    Contrast with E88 which uses outer products and a scalar decay. -/\n   112→noncomputable def e1hHeadUpdate (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n   113→    (input : Fin d → ℝ) : E1HHeadState d :=\n   114→  let wx_x := head.inputProj.mulVec input          -- W_x · x_t\n   115→  let wh_h := head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state    -- W_h · h_{t-1}\n   116→  let preActivation := fun i => wx_x i + wh_h i + head.bias i\n   117→  vecTanh preActivation\n   118→\n   119→/-- E1H state after T timesteps for a single head -/\n   120→noncomputable def e1hHeadStateAfterT (head : E1HHead d d) (T : ℕ)\n   121→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HHeadState d := fun _ => 0) :\n   122→    E1HHeadState d :=\n   123→  List.foldl (fun s x => e1hHeadUpdate head s x) initState (List.ofFn inputs)\n   124→\n   125→/-- Multi-head E1H state evolution.\n   126→    Each head evolves independently — same structural property as E88. -/\n   127→noncomputable def e1hMultiHeadState {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   128→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HState h d := fun _ => fun _ => 0) :\n   129→    E1HState h d :=\n   130→  fun head_idx => e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads head_idx) T inputs (initState head_idx)\n   131→\n   132→/-! ## Part 3: Boundedness of E1H States -/\n   133→\n   134→/-- E1H state elements are bounded in (-1, 1) after each update.\n   135→    This follows immediately from the tanh nonlinearity. -/\n   136→theorem e1h_state_bounded (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n   137→    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n   138→    ∀ i : Fin d, |e1hHeadUpdate head state input i| < 1 := by\n   139→  intro i\n   140→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n   141→  exact Activation.tanh_bounded _\n   142→\n   143→/-- E1H state elements are in the open interval (-1, 1) -/\n   144→theorem e1h_state_in_unit_interval (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n   145→    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n   146→    ∀ i : Fin d, -1 < e1hHeadUpdate head state input i ∧\n   147→                 e1hHeadUpdate head state input i < 1 := by\n   148→  intro i\n   149→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n   150→  have hb := Activation.tanh_bounded (head.inputProj.mulVec input i +\n   151→                                       head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state i +\n   152→                                       head.bias i)\n   153→  exact abs_lt.mp hb\n   154→\n   155→/-! ## Part 4: Head Independence -/\n   156→\n   157→/-- **E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n   158→\n   159→Each head's state update depends only on:\n   160→1. Its own previous state h^k_{t-1}\n   161→2. The current input x_t (through its own W_x^k, W_h^k, b^k parameters)\n   162→\n   163→There is NO cross-head communication in the state dynamics. -/\n   164→theorem e1h_heads_independent {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   165→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin h) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2)\n   166→    (head2' : E1HHead d d) :\n   167→    -- The state of head h1 is unaffected when head h2's parameters are replaced\n   168→    e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n   169→    e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   170→      ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n   171→      T inputs := by\n   172→  simp only [if_neg h_neq]\n   173→\n   174→/-- Heads can be computed in parallel (no sequential dependency between heads) -/\n   175→theorem e1h_heads_parallel_computable {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n   176→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n   177→    ∀ h1 h2 : Fin h, h1 ≠ h2 →\n   178→      let state := e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs\n   179→      state h1 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs (fun _ => 0) ∧\n   180→      state h2 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h2) T inputs (fun _ => 0) := by\n   181→  intro h1 h2 _\n   182→  exact ⟨rfl, rfl⟩\n   183→\n   184→/-! ## Part 5: Temporal Depth -/\n   185→\n   186→/-- E1H has compositional depth T per layer (same as E88).\n   187→\n   188→The state at time T is computed by T sequential applications of the nonlinear\n   189→update function. The compositional depth grows with sequence length, identical\n   190→to E88 and unlike linear-temporal models (which have fixed depth 1). -/\n   191→theorem e1h_temporal_depth (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n   192→    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length\n   193→    let e1h_depth := T\n   194→    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n   195→    let linear_depth := 1\n   196→    e1h_depth > linear_depth := h_T\n   197→\n   198→/-- E1H compositional depth equals E88 compositional depth.\n   199→    Both architectures produce T sequential nonlinear applications per layer. -/\n   200→theorem e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n   201→    -- Both E1H and E88 have depth T\n   202→    let e1h_depth := T\n   203→    let e88_depth := T\n   204→    e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n   205→\n   206→/-! ## Part 6: State Dimension Comparison -/\n   207→\n   208→/-- E1H state dimension per head: D scalars (a vector).\n   209→\n   210→This is the KEY structural difference from E88. -/\n   211→def e1hStateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim\n   212→\n   213→/-- E88 state dimension per head: D × D scalars (a matrix). -/\n   214→def e88StateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim * headDim\n   215→\n   216→/-- **E88 has strictly more state capacity than E1H** (when headDim ≥ 2).\n   217→\n   218→For headDim ≥ 2, E88's D×D matrix state contains strictly more scalar\n   219→parameters than E1H's D-vector state.\n   220→\n   221→This is the formal statement that motivates:\n   222→- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: Prove E88 matrix state strictly exceeds E1H vector state -/\n   223→theorem e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state (headDim : ℕ) (h : headDim ≥ 2) :\n   224→    e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim < e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n   225→  simp only [e1hStateScalarsPerHead, e88StateScalarsPerHead]\n   226→  -- headDim < headDim * headDim when headDim ≥ 2\n   227→  nlinarith [Nat.mul_pos (by omega : 0 < headDim) (by omega : 0 < headDim)]\n   228→\n   229→/-- E88 state advantage factor: D times more capacity per head -/\n   230→theorem e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio (headDim : ℕ) :\n   231→    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n   232→  simp only [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]\n   233→\n   234→/-! ## Part 7: Total State Comparison -/\n   235→\n   236→/-- Total E1H state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim -/\n   237→def e1hTotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim\n   238→\n   239→/-- Total E88 state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim × headDim -/\n   240→def e88TotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim * headDim\n   241→\n   242→/-- E88 total state exceeds E1H total state when headDim ≥ 2 -/\n   243→theorem e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h (numHeads headDim : ℕ)\n   244→    (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hD : headDim ≥ 2) :\n   245→    e1hTotalState numHeads headDim < e88TotalState numHeads headDim := by\n   246→  simp only [e1hTotalState, e88TotalState]\n   247→  have hd1 : 1 < headDim := by omega\n   248→  have hn1 : 0 < numHeads := by omega\n   249→  nlinarith [Nat.mul_lt_mul_of_pos_left (by nlinarith : headDim < headDim * headDim) hn1]\n   250→\n   251→/-! ## Part 8: Relationship to E88 -/\n   252→\n   253→/-- **E1H and E88 share the same temporal structure**.\n   254→\n   255→Both architectures:\n   256→1. Apply H independent heads\n   257→2. Each head runs T sequential nonlinear recurrence steps\n   258→3. No cross-head state communication\n   259→\n   260→The key difference is the state SHAPE: E1H has vector state (D), E88 has matrix state (D×D). -/\n   261→theorem e1h_e88_shared_temporal_structure (T : ℕ) (headDim : ℕ) :\n   262→    -- Both have temporal depth T\n   263→    T = T ∧\n   264→    -- E88 has headDim times more state per head\n   265→    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim :=\n   266→  ⟨rfl, by simp [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]⟩\n   267→\n   268→/-! ## Appendix: Architecture Comparison Summary\n   269→\n   270→```\n   271→                    E1H               E88\n   272→State per head:     D-vector          D×D matrix\n   273→State scalars:      D                 D²\n   274→Update:             tanh(W_x·x +      tanh(α·S +\n   275→                        W_h·h + b)        δ·outer(v,k))\n   276→Decay factor:       None              α ∈ (0, 2)\n   277→Input coupling:     Full W_x matrix   Rank-1 outer product\n   278→Temporal depth:     T per layer       T per layer\n   279→Head independence:  Yes               Yes\n   280→State bounded:      (-1,1)^D          (-1,1)^{D×D}\n   281→\n   282→For downstream tasks:\n   283→- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: E88 state D² > E1H state D (for D ≥ 2)\n   284→- e1h-temporal-theorems: E1H temporal depth = E88 temporal depth = T\n   285→```\n   286→-/\n   287→\n   288→end E1H\n   289→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6b651675-b913-4caf-818d-91bf4c46cc1f","uuid":"ff2216a2-fff9-4751-b4e0-07e7698805f7","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HDefinition.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\n\n/-!\n# E1H: Multi-Head Elman (Vector State)\n\nThis file provides the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for E1H architecture formalization.\n\n## E1H Architecture\n\nE1H is a multi-head Elman recurrent network with:\n1. **Multi-head vector states**: H heads, each with a vector state of dimension D\n2. **Elman temporal dynamics**: h_t = tanh(W_x·x_t + W_h·h_{t-1} + b)\n3. **Independent head evolution**: Each head runs autonomous temporal dynamics\n4. **No decay factor**: Unlike E88, there is no separate α decay scalar\n5. **No outer product**: Unlike E88, the state update is not an outer product operation\n\n## Core Update Rule\n\nFor each head h:\n```\nh_t^h = tanh(W_x^h · x_t + W_h^h · h_{t-1}^h + b^h)\n```\n\nWhere:\n- h ∈ ℝ^D: Vector hidden state for head h (NOT a D×D matrix like E88)\n- W_x ∈ ℝ^{D×inputDim}: Input projection matrix\n- W_h ∈ ℝ^{D×D}: Recurrence (state-to-state) weight matrix\n- b ∈ ℝ^D: Bias vector\n- tanh: Applied element-wise to the resulting vector\n\n## Key Differences from E88\n\n| Property        | E88                      | E1H                           |\n|-----------------|--------------------------|-------------------------------|\n| State shape     | D×D matrix per head      | D-vector per head             |\n| State dimension | D² scalars per head      | D scalars per head            |\n| Update          | tanh(α·S + δ·outer(v,k)) | tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)      |\n| Decay factor    | α ∈ (0, 2)               | None (folded into W_h)        |\n| Input coupling  | Outer product (rank-1)   | Full matrix-vector product    |\n| Parameters      | K_h, V_h + scalars       | W_x_h, W_h_h, b_h             |\n\n## Key Properties\n\n1. **Shared Temporal Depth**: Both E1H and E88 have compositional depth T per layer\n2. **Vector vs Matrix Capacity**: E88 state has D² entries vs E1H's D entries per head\n3. **Head Independence**: Each head evolves independently (like E88)\n4. **Tanh Boundedness**: h_t ∈ [-1, 1]^D at all times\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `e1hHeadUpdate` - Core per-head update function\n* `e1hHeadStateAfterT` - Single-head state after T steps\n* `e1hMultiHeadState` - Multi-head state evolution\n* `e1h_heads_independent` - Heads evolve independently\n* `e1h_state_bounded` - States are bounded in [-1, 1]^D\n* `e1h_temporal_depth` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n* `e1h_vector_state_dimension` - E1H state has D scalars per head (vs D² for E88)\n\n-/\n\nnamespace E1H\n\nopen Real Matrix Finset BigOperators\n\n/-! ## Part 1: E1H Core Architecture -/\n\n/-- E1H single-head configuration.\n    Each head maintains a D-dimensional vector state (not a matrix like E88). -/\nstructure E1HHead (inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n  /-- Input projection matrix W_x: headDim × inputDim -/\n  inputProj : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin inputDim) ℝ\n  /-- Recurrence weight matrix W_h: headDim × headDim -/\n  recurrenceWeight : Matrix (Fin headDim) (Fin headDim) ℝ\n  /-- Bias vector b: headDim -/\n  bias : Fin headDim → ℝ\n\n/-- E1H multi-head model.\n    H independent Elman RNN heads with shared input via a single in-projection. -/\nstructure E1HModel (numHeads inputDim headDim : ℕ) where\n  /-- Configuration for each head -/\n  heads : Fin numHeads → E1HHead inputDim headDim\n  /-- Output projection from all head states concatenated -/\n  outputProj : Matrix (Fin inputDim) (Fin (numHeads * headDim)) ℝ\n\n/-- Vector hidden state for a single E1H head.\n    This is a D-dimensional vector, NOT a D×D matrix like E88's HeadState. -/\nabbrev E1HHeadState (headDim : ℕ) := Fin headDim → ℝ\n\n/-- E1H state for all heads: a vector state per head. -/\nabbrev E1HState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) := Fin numHeads → E1HHeadState headDim\n\n/-! ## Part 2: E1H State Update Dynamics -/\n\n/-- Element-wise tanh applied to a vector -/\nnoncomputable def vecTanh {n : ℕ} (v : Fin n → ℝ) : Fin n → ℝ :=\n  fun i => tanh (v i)\n\n/-- Single-head E1H state update: h' = tanh(W_x·x + W_h·h + b)\n    This is the standard Elman recurrence with full matrix projections.\n    Contrast with E88 which uses outer products and a scalar decay. -/\nnoncomputable def e1hHeadUpdate (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n    (input : Fin d → ℝ) : E1HHeadState d :=\n  let wx_x := head.inputProj.mulVec input          -- W_x · x_t\n  let wh_h := head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state    -- W_h · h_{t-1}\n  let preActivation := fun i => wx_x i + wh_h i + head.bias i\n  vecTanh preActivation\n\n/-- E1H state after T timesteps for a single head -/\nnoncomputable def e1hHeadStateAfterT (head : E1HHead d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HHeadState d := fun _ => 0) :\n    E1HHeadState d :=\n  List.foldl (fun s x => e1hHeadUpdate head s x) initState (List.ofFn inputs)\n\n/-- Multi-head E1H state evolution.\n    Each head evolves independently — same structural property as E88. -/\nnoncomputable def e1hMultiHeadState {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (initState : E1HState h d := fun _ => fun _ => 0) :\n    E1HState h d :=\n  fun head_idx => e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads head_idx) T inputs (initState head_idx)\n\n/-! ## Part 3: Boundedness of E1H States -/\n\n/-- E1H state elements are bounded in (-1, 1) after each update.\n    This follows immediately from the tanh nonlinearity. -/\ntheorem e1h_state_bounded (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n    ∀ i : Fin d, |e1hHeadUpdate head state input i| < 1 := by\n  intro i\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n  exact Activation.tanh_bounded _\n\n/-- E1H state elements are in the open interval (-1, 1) -/\ntheorem e1h_state_in_unit_interval (head : E1HHead d d) (state : E1HHeadState d)\n    (input : Fin d → ℝ) :\n    ∀ i : Fin d, -1 < e1hHeadUpdate head state input i ∧\n                 e1hHeadUpdate head state input i < 1 := by\n  intro i\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh]\n  have hb := Activation.tanh_bounded (head.inputProj.mulVec input i +\n                                       head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec state i +\n                                       head.bias i)\n  exact abs_lt.mp hb\n\n/-! ## Part 4: Head Independence -/\n\n/-- **E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n\nEach head's state update depends only on:\n1. Its own previous state h^k_{t-1}\n2. The current input x_t (through its own W_x^k, W_h^k, b^k parameters)\n\nThere is NO cross-head communication in the state dynamics. -/\ntheorem e1h_heads_independent {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin h) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2)\n    (head2' : E1HHead d d) :\n    -- The state of head h1 is unaffected when head h2's parameters are replaced\n    e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n    e1hHeadStateAfterT\n      ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n      T inputs := by\n  simp only [if_neg h_neq]\n\n/-- Heads can be computed in parallel (no sequential dependency between heads) -/\ntheorem e1h_heads_parallel_computable {h : ℕ} (model : E1HModel h d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n    ∀ h1 h2 : Fin h, h1 ≠ h2 →\n      let state := e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs\n      state h1 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs (fun _ => 0) ∧\n      state h2 = e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h2) T inputs (fun _ => 0) := by\n  intro h1 h2 _\n  exact ⟨rfl, rfl⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 5: Temporal Depth -/\n\n/-- E1H has compositional depth T per layer (same as E88).\n\nThe state at time T is computed by T sequential applications of the nonlinear\nupdate function. The compositional depth grows with sequence length, identical\nto E88 and unlike linear-temporal models (which have fixed depth 1). -/\ntheorem e1h_temporal_depth (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    let linear_depth := 1\n    e1h_depth > linear_depth := h_T\n\n/-- E1H compositional depth equals E88 compositional depth.\n    Both architectures produce T sequential nonlinear applications per layer. -/\ntheorem e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n    -- Both E1H and E88 have depth T\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    let e88_depth := T\n    e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n\n/-! ## Part 6: State Dimension Comparison -/\n\n/-- E1H state dimension per head: D scalars (a vector).\n\nThis is the KEY structural difference from E88. -/\ndef e1hStateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim\n\n/-- E88 state dimension per head: D × D scalars (a matrix). -/\ndef e88StateScalarsPerHead (headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := headDim * headDim\n\n/-- **E88 has strictly more state capacity than E1H** (when headDim ≥ 2).\n\nFor headDim ≥ 2, E88's D×D matrix state contains strictly more scalar\nparameters than E1H's D-vector state.\n\nThis is the formal statement that motivates:\n- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: Prove E88 matrix state strictly exceeds E1H vector state -/\ntheorem e88_state_exceeds_e1h_state (headDim : ℕ) (h : headDim ≥ 2) :\n    e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim < e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n  simp only [e1hStateScalarsPerHead, e88StateScalarsPerHead]\n  -- headDim < headDim * headDim when headDim ≥ 2\n  nlinarith [Nat.mul_pos (by omega : 0 < headDim) (by omega : 0 < headDim)]\n\n/-- E88 state advantage factor: D times more capacity per head -/\ntheorem e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio (headDim : ℕ) :\n    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim := by\n  simp only [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]\n\n/-! ## Part 7: Total State Comparison -/\n\n/-- Total E1H state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim -/\ndef e1hTotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim\n\n/-- Total E88 state scalars across all heads: numHeads × headDim × headDim -/\ndef e88TotalState (numHeads headDim : ℕ) : ℕ := numHeads * headDim * headDim\n\n/-- E88 total state exceeds E1H total state when headDim ≥ 2 -/\ntheorem e88_total_state_exceeds_e1h (numHeads headDim : ℕ)\n    (hH : numHeads ≥ 1) (hD : headDim ≥ 2) :\n    e1hTotalState numHeads headDim < e88TotalState numHeads headDim := by\n  simp only [e1hTotalState, e88TotalState]\n  have hd1 : 1 < headDim := by omega\n  have hn1 : 0 < numHeads := by omega\n  nlinarith [Nat.mul_lt_mul_of_pos_left (by nlinarith : headDim < headDim * headDim) hn1]\n\n/-! ## Part 8: Relationship to E88 -/\n\n/-- **E1H and E88 share the same temporal structure**.\n\nBoth architectures:\n1. Apply H independent heads\n2. Each head runs T sequential nonlinear recurrence steps\n3. No cross-head state communication\n\nThe key difference is the state SHAPE: E1H has vector state (D), E88 has matrix state (D×D). -/\ntheorem e1h_e88_shared_temporal_structure (T : ℕ) (headDim : ℕ) :\n    -- Both have temporal depth T\n    T = T ∧\n    -- E88 has headDim times more state per head\n    e88StateScalarsPerHead headDim = headDim * e1hStateScalarsPerHead headDim :=\n  ⟨rfl, by simp [e88StateScalarsPerHead, e1hStateScalarsPerHead]⟩\n\n/-! ## Appendix: Architecture Comparison Summary\n\n```\n                    E1H               E88\nState per head:     D-vector          D×D matrix\nState scalars:      D                 D²\nUpdate:             tanh(W_x·x +      tanh(α·S +\n                        W_h·h + b)        δ·outer(v,k))\nDecay factor:       None              α ∈ (0, 2)\nInput coupling:     Full W_x matrix   Rank-1 outer product\nTemporal depth:     T per layer       T per layer\nHead independence:  Yes               Yes\nState bounded:      (-1,1)^D          (-1,1)^{D×D}\n\nFor downstream tasks:\n- e88-exceeds-e1h-capacity: E88 state D² > E1H state D (for D ≥ 2)\n- e1h-temporal-theorems: E1H temporal depth = E88 temporal depth = T\n```\n-/\n\nend E1H\n","numLines":289,"startLine":1,"totalLines":289}}}
